There are also special mail-tags that ha: There are also special mail-tags that have specific names, but don’t have corresponding form-tags. They are used to represent the meta information of form submissions like the submitter’s IP address or the URL of the page.
A mail-tag is also a short code enclosed: A mail-tag is also a short code enclosed in square brackets that you can use in every Mail and Mail (2) field. A mail-tag represents a user input value through an input field of a corresponding form-tag.
While form-tags have a comparatively com: While form-tags have a comparatively complex syntax, you don’t need to know the syntax to add form-tags because you can use the straightforward tag generator (Generate Tag button on this screen).
A form-tag is a short code enclosed in s: A form-tag is a short code enclosed in square brackets used in a form content. A form-tag generally represents an input field, and its components can be separated into four parts: type, name, options, and values. Contact Form 7 supports several types of form-tags including text fields, number fields, date fields, checkboxes, radio buttons, menus, file-uploading fields, CAPTCHAs, and quiz fields.
<strong>Additional Settings<\/strong> pr: Additional Settings provides a place where you can customise the behaviour of this contact form by adding code snippets.
In <strong>Messages<\/strong>, you can e: In Messages, you can edit various types of messages used for this contact form. These messages are relatively short messages, like a validation error message you see when you leave a required field blank.
<strong>Mail (2)<\/strong> is an additio: Mail (2) is an additional mail template that works similarly to Mail. Mail (2) is different in that it is sent only when Mail has been sent successfully.
<strong>Mail<\/strong> manages a mail te: Mail manages a mail template (headers and message body) that this contact form will send when users submit it. You can use Contact Form 7’s mail-tags here.
<strong>Form<\/strong> is a content of H: Form is a content of an HTML form. You can use arbitrary HTML, which is allowed inside a form element. You can also use Contact Form 7’s form-tags here.
<strong>Title<\/strong> is the title of: Title is the title of a contact form. This title is only used for labelling a contact form, and can be edited.

<strong>Duplicate<\/strong> - Clones tha: Duplicate - Clones that contact form. A cloned contact form inherits all content from the original, but has a different ID.
<strong>Edit<\/strong> - Navigates to th: Edit - Navigates to the editing screen for that contact form. You can also reach that screen by clicking on the contact form title.

Each contact form has a unique ID and Contact Form 7 shortcode ([contact-form-7 ...]). To insert a contact form into a post or a text widget, insert the shortcode into the target.
